00:06:30.839 --> 00:06:33.640
then you won't make any progress within the organization.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:43.959
So, we, the data science team at the City of Reykjavik, we have this momentum from the City

00:06:43.959 --> 00:06:51.559
Council, but we need to bring the action to the other departments in the sense that we need to

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:59.559
show them how we bring value. And I feel like this is for at least the team or the team leader,

00:06:59.799 --> 00:07:04.679
or somebody has to be responsible for this aspect of the data science operations.

00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:16.359
And bringing value isn't only your responsibility. It's your and your clients' or your

00:07:16.359 --> 00:07:22.839
stakeholders' responsibility. And it can only happen in a dialogue and in an open discussion

00:07:22.839 --> 00:07:28.200
with your stakeholders. Let me give you an example. Like, we have various stakeholders

00:07:28.359 --> 00:07:36.279
at the City. The residents of Reykjavik City are the largest stakeholder. But let's demystify this.

00:07:36.279 --> 00:07:42.359
Let's take an easy example. Like, one of our biggest stakeholders that is within the city

00:07:42.359 --> 00:07:47.000
are all departments like school and leisure. And they know their business. They know what

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:56.040
they're about. And we can't, like, do data science for them without working with them

00:07:56.040 --> 00:08:00.760
and having a dialogue with them such that they understand the value they're bringing.

00:08:01.399 --> 00:08:11.399
Like, how are we adding to your operation with data science? And so being in this role,

00:08:11.399 --> 00:08:15.720
you have to be okay with, hey, I need to explain things that are obvious to me

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:24.760
and realize that not everybody is as excited about data as you. And be okay with that.

00:08:25.399 --> 00:08:31.160
You need to have a discussion with all stakeholders. Like, hey, this is great. You

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:37.000
can do this. Did you realize that? And this is awesome. And they need to fit it into their own

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:47.000
framework. And I feel like in my experience, like, be energetic about this. Be mindful of

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:52.520
their needs. And if they're, like, bringing up the wall and being difficult, there might be a

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:58.919
reason for that. That has nothing to do with you or data science. It's all about them. And slowly

00:08:58.919 --> 00:09:06.599
but surely, you can bring value. And realize that people are different. And what I find amazing in

00:09:06.599 --> 00:09:14.840
this job is, like, data science is more about people than it is about AI. Isn't that weird?

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:20.280
You can't just sit in some corner and train AI models and expect things to be amazing.

00:09:20.919 --> 00:09:29.000
So, you have to have this in your team. So, a few words about my awesome team. And I feel so

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:37.159
privileged to be a part of it. So, I have thoughts on how to assemble a team like this. And

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:45.159
of course, there's certain categories and certain domains that you want to make sure

00:09:45.159 --> 00:09:52.039
you have checked in some box. And of course, you need to have, like, these data engineers.

00:09:52.039 --> 00:09:59.000
They are responsible for getting data into some sort of domain, like a data warehouse or

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:04.520
data lake or whatever technology you're using. Their responsibility for the underlying framework.

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:12.760
And I often have, like, this metaphor for using a data pyramid. And the first layer of the pyramid

00:10:12.760 --> 00:10:17.559
that you're trying to build are the data foundations. Getting data, cleaning it,

00:10:17.559 --> 00:10:22.760
and maintaining it. All of these things. I'm assuming that everybody here is relatively

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:30.840
familiar with that. And the skill set there is a bit different than the skill set that you're

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:37.320
looking for when you're looking for state scientists. But there is an intersection

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:41.719
between those two domains. But they aren't necessarily wholly the same.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:51.559
So, once you have these strong data foundations, and then you need to bring in the data scientists,

00:10:51.559 --> 00:10:58.039
the talent set that can go into the data and find patterns and bring value.

00:10:58.679 --> 00:11:05.080
And I think it's incredibly important that the data scientists are okay with maintaining

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:11.880
an open dialogue with the stakeholders and explaining things that are obvious to them.

00:11:11.880 --> 00:11:17.159
Like, hey, you know, this is the mean and this is the median. And just be okay with that. Put

00:11:17.159 --> 00:11:24.359
on your teacher's hat and enjoy the ride. And I think it's much more about that than training

00:11:24.359 --> 00:11:30.200
extremely complicated models, at least in some cases. And I guess this varies between business

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:37.479
domains. But at the city, most of the effort is in the dialogue. But we sometimes hit problems

00:11:37.479 --> 00:11:45.239
that are difficult in some sense, are involved. And that's fantastic. But that's just part of

00:11:45.239 --> 00:11:50.760
the game. That's not the whole game. And that is the second layer in the pyramid. And I think the

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:58.840
third layer is what I call and I think in the literature is called data ops. And that is

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:05.159
operationalizing some of your products, your data products, and your data products might be

00:12:05.159 --> 00:12:11.719
APIs, APIs that you expose to your clients. It might be connections into Excel or Power BI or

00:12:11.719 --> 00:12:19.880
whatever. It might be like shiny dashboards. And we use a lot of shiny dashboards. And in our case,

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:28.280
the operational side is maintaining and designing and operationalizing dashboards and also

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:35.320
access to models and access to plots. So in our particular case, it's an RStudio Connect.

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:43.799
And so all of these things are aiming to, you're trying to build this pyramid to get to the top

00:12:43.799 --> 00:12:49.239
part of it, which is bringing value. You can have all these nice things. But if you aren't bringing

00:12:49.239 --> 00:12:56.039
value to somebody, and I'd like to emphasize that it's not necessarily only monetary value. It can

00:12:56.039 --> 00:13:01.799
be value in the form of better services, in a better experience for the residents of your city,

00:13:01.799 --> 00:13:07.400
like in our case, you need to define it. And you need to be able to measure it. And then you need

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:16.119
to live by it. We brought value through this product in this sense. I feel like when you are,

00:13:16.679 --> 00:13:21.799
when everybody in the team realizes that, you get this positive feedback loop into your team

00:13:21.799 --> 00:13:28.280
from your clients, that you and your team belong to something bigger than yourself, and bigger than

00:13:28.280 --> 00:13:35.880
your team. And then, at least in my case, and I think I can talk for the team as well. And

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:42.280
then you're more, let's say energetic about going to work the next day.

