00:24:29.319 --> 00:24:38.839
and it's at this time. And I predict that guests that are coming now should stay on average 90

00:24:38.839 --> 00:24:45.880
minutes. So then we count them out after 90 minutes. And so we count in and then we have

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:51.560
a model that counts out. So we have an accumulated distribution with pluses and accumulated

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:59.000
distribution with minuses. And then we can calculate some kind of estimate on how many

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:04.359
are in the swimming pool during every hour. But the thing is, here we need to think about,

00:25:04.359 --> 00:25:14.119
here comes, now we think about this project as a data scientist, or we need to zoom out a bit

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:24.199
and ask, okay, where's the value? The value is knowing approximately at which capacity

00:25:24.199 --> 00:25:29.800
the swimming pool is at. I only need to know whether it's like 70, 80% capacity or 20%.

00:25:30.439 --> 00:25:37.719
I don't need to know as a guest whether there are 50 guests or 52 guests. Does that make sense?

00:25:37.719 --> 00:25:41.800
Like you might be discouraged to go to the swimming pool if you see it's at full capacity,

00:25:42.520 --> 00:25:51.079
or you might not. It depends on your needs. So then we are okay with errors, but we still

00:25:51.079 --> 00:26:02.359
need to have some way to predict within certain degree of some estimations and with some degree

00:26:02.359 --> 00:26:09.079
of uncertainty. So that's how we do it. We applied that model to the other swimming pools,

00:26:09.079 --> 00:26:17.400
and we are currently asking those swimming pool executives to evaluate whether this makes any

00:26:17.400 --> 00:26:23.079
sense. But there is a catch, and this is why it is one of our favourite projects.

00:26:24.359 --> 00:26:32.599
In Lerpersloe, that doesn't count out, that counts out, sometime during the day, the staff

00:26:33.560 --> 00:26:37.400
says, to help with it, there are too many guests here, we're just going to open the gates

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:44.760
and re-evaluate in the morning how many guests were. So we need to do some estimation on how

00:26:44.760 --> 00:26:51.079
correct the data is. I'm not going to go into those details, they're very minute and weird,

00:26:51.959 --> 00:27:00.920
but I really like that. So yeah, we have like this model running in our studio environment.

00:27:01.640 --> 00:27:09.719
It's like the data comes in, it comes onto our studio computer that's in the Azure cloud,

00:27:09.719 --> 00:27:15.319
so it's a virtual machine, and then it queries the model, like, hey, how many,

00:27:16.199 --> 00:27:23.079
like, for how long should this guest stay? Oh, he's going to stay for 90 minutes. And then it

00:27:23.079 --> 00:27:29.719
will do the aggregation of the pluses and minuses and then give the feedback back to the API.

00:27:29.719 --> 00:27:36.119
And I just think it's really cool. It's data science and some arithmetic.

