surprised. And it's something that's like, yeah, like 20 years ago, we can do that. And so like

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:25.560
when they don't even know what's possible, how do they know really what they want? And how do you

00:45:25.560 --> 00:45:36.679
kind of tease that out of them? That's the trick, isn't it? Is to find this common ground with

00:45:36.679 --> 00:45:41.399
somebody who's an expert in their own business and their operations and knows nothing about data

00:45:41.399 --> 00:45:51.879
science. And I think the short answer is there is no one single way to do this. But the long answer

00:45:51.879 --> 00:46:00.040
is have many discussions and be aware of continuous development processes. So you can start

00:46:00.040 --> 00:46:07.879
out by doing something simple. And did you mean this? And have a dialogue on that. Then meet again

00:46:07.879 --> 00:46:16.919
and meet again and meet again and build something simple and build upon it. So I'm really fond of

00:46:16.919 --> 00:46:26.040
this concept of continuous development and building up some things like step by step. And

00:46:26.040 --> 00:46:33.000
I think what happens in a process like that, if you have a good relation and open dialogue with

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:41.879
your stakeholder, is they realize that, hey, what? That's awesome, right? And just to give you a

00:46:41.879 --> 00:46:47.800
super simple example, like one of these dashboards that we are building, and that has nothing to do

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:55.560
with machine learning or anything like that, like we use a package in R called Plotly to build up

